<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[tokumaru]]></name></author>
<updated>2011-04-14T14:04:14-07:00</updated>
<published>2011-04-14T14:04:14-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7654&amp;p=76726#p76726</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7654&amp;p=76726#p76726"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Status bar problem]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7654&amp;p=76726#p76726"><![CDATA[
Also, because you change $2006 when changing the palette, you can't reset the scroll with $2005 writes alone, you have to reset $2006 too.<br /><br />If you want to avoid glitches while updating the palette mid-frame, you have to do it during HBlank, like Dwedit said. But since the time of one HBlank is only enough to change about 4 colors, you will probably need a few scanlines to modify them all.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Denine wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />But I can't find info how to wait for Hblank.<br />Can anyone explain, pleeease:)<br /></div><br />You have to guess/calculate based on the location of the sprite hit. HBlank comes right after the 256 pixels of the scanline, and each CPU cycle corresponds to 3 PPU cycles (pixels). Just calculate how many pixels are there from the place of the hit until the end of the scanline and convert that into CPU cycles and you know how much you have to "wait" (the quotes are because you don't necessarily wait, you can perform useful tasks during that time, like setting addresses and pre-loading colors).<br /><br />You should also take into consideration the time taken by the loop that checks the hit flag, because the flag can change at any time during that loop and it might take you as much as the total time of the loop to detect the change, so you must consider that time as a possible error in your timing.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=95">tokumaru</a> — Thu Apr 14, 2011 2:04 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
